{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The wait time between retries doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is backoff math/policy logic at a single function boundary (attempt count + config -> delay). Behavior text is purely computational; no module handoff is required to expose failure. Higher levels were rejected because the behavior does not require real HTTP, timers, or cross-module state.","test_description":"Test `computeBackoffDelay(attempt, baseDelay, maxDelay)` (or equivalent) with consecutive failure counts and assert exponential growth then cap at max.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes the appropriate wait time before the next attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at a module boundary: HTTP response classification (rate-limit detection) must feed retry/backoff policy correctly. A single pure-function unit test can miss wiring errors (wrong status/header mapping, wrong handoff). System was rejected because in-process stub responses reproduce this failure; no real network/OS behavior is required by the behavior text.","test_description":"Wire retry middleware + response parser + backoff policy with a stub transport returning a rate-limit response (e.g., 429 and optional retry metadata). Assert retry branch is taken and computed wait matches policy/config.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result to the caller transparently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This verifies orchestration across retry scheduler, request replay, and result propagation. The real failure is often in handoff/state preservation (method/body/headers/caller promise resolution), not one local function. System rejected: behavior text does not require real HTTP stack; deterministic stub transport + controlled clock catches resend/path bugs.","test_description":"Use fake timers and a stub transport that returns rate-limit once, then success. Assert the second attempt reuses the original request payload and `call()` resolves with the success value without caller-visible retry plumbing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.87,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After the configured maximum number of retries, the client returns a typed `QuotaExhaustedError` rather than a generic error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The typed error is an external contract produced after retry-loop exhaustion, so you need loop counting + exhaustion path + error mapping wired together. Unit-only checks of the error class can miss off-by-one or wrong terminal-path mapping. System rejected because repeated stubbed rate-limit responses reproduce the exact failure without real network.","test_description":"Configure low max retries; stub transport to always rate-limit. Execute `call()` and assert rejection is specifically `QuotaExhaustedError` after expected attempt count (not generic/transport error).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full retry chain — initial call, backoff retries, quota tracking — terminates correctly and does not loop indefinitely before surfacing the error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is multi-module local orchestration (retry state machine + quota tracker + termination condition). Real failure is typically in state handoff/termination guards, which unit tests on isolated helpers can miss. System rejected because fake timers and stub transport can deterministically detect non-termination/over-retry without OS/network dependencies.","test_description":"Run the complete in-process chain with always-rate-limited responses and fake clock. Assert attempts stop at configured bound, quota state reaches expected terminal condition, and error surfaces; fail if extra attempts occur.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Requests issued concurrently from multiple async callers in the same process all draw from the same shared quota bucket.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on shared state across concurrent callers and module wiring (client instances/call sites -> shared quota manager). Unit tests on one object method cannot reliably expose cross-caller sharing bugs. System rejected by behavior text 'in the same process': no real external infra is required; in-process concurrency tests reproduce failure.","test_description":"Launch multiple concurrent `call()` invocations using a shared client/quota manager with stub transport. Assert global quota consumption reflects combined demand and no caller bypasses the shared bucket.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.93,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When multiple requests are waiting to be sent, they are dispatched in the order they were originally submitted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Ordering is a queue/orchestrator property across async scheduling + dispatcher modules, not a single pure algorithm in isolation. Unit tests may validate comparator logic but miss enqueue/dequeue race wiring bugs. System rejected because deterministic in-process scheduler/fake timers can expose FIFO violations without real network/OS primitives.","test_description":"Queue several calls rapidly while quota/rate-limit forces waiting; use stub transport and controlled clock. Assert dispatch start order matches submission order (FIFO) under contention.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.89,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
